	url = {https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/17480485241296682},
	doi = {10.1177/17480485241296682},
	abstract = {This study analyzed “China threat” coverage in US media and examined how such coverage affected public perception of China from 1999 to 2019. We retrieved 15 national polls on perceptions of “China threat” together with 30,795 China-related news articles published before each poll. Media discourse related to “China threat” was coded into ideological, military, and economic second-level agendas using computational methods. We ﬁrst tracked how “China threat” waxed and waned in media discourse over this period. Second, we examined whether the salience of “China threat” in the media has agenda-setting effects on public opinion. We found the economic threat agenda is correlated with the American public perception of China’s threat at a marginally signiﬁcant level and is signiﬁcantly correlated with the Democrats’ threat perception.},
	language = {en},
	urldate = {2025-03-30},
	journal = {International Communication Gazette},
	author = {Zheng, Jingwei and Du, Ying Roselyn and Xu, Miao},
	month = nov,
	year = {2024},
	pages = {17480485241296682},
	annote = {Brief Summary:
Zheng et al. (2024) conduct a large-scale computational content analysis of U.S. media coverage (1999–2019) to examine how the “China threat” narrative evolved across economic, military, and ideological dimensions. They found a significant increase in the economic threat narrative, particularly after the year 2008, and documented how media portrayals correlated with shifts in American public opinion—especially economic concerns resonating strongly with Democratic respondents. Using advanced machine learning techniques (BERT), the authors demonstrate how implicit threat narratives (beyond explicit mentions) significantly shape public perceptions of China.

Evaluation:
This paper is particularly valuable to my project for its robust methodological integration of computational text analysis (BERT), effectively capturing subtle shifts in nationalist narratives over time. It clearly establish an agenda-setting link between media framing of economic threats and public opinion, specifically highlighting partisan divides. I will expand by comparing similar threat framing in relation to multiple geopolitical rivals (notably Russia alongside China) and systematically examining differences between left- and right-leaning U.S. media. 
},
