	journal = {International Communication Gazette},
	author = {Golan, Guy J and Lukito, Josephine},
	month = dec,
	year = {2015},
	pages = {754--772},
	annote = {Brief Summary:
Golan and Lukito (2015) analyze how two elite American newspapers—the New York Times (NYT) and the Wall Street Journal (WSJ)—frame China’s emergence as a global power through opinion articles. Their textual analysis identifies significant differences: NYT tends to portray China primarily as an economic partner with structural limitations and internal sociopolitical problems, emphasizing cooperation over rivalry. In contrast, WSJ frames China as a direct geopolitical and economic threat to U.S. interests, employing aggressive rhetoric and emphasizing China’s nationalist ambitions and illegal economic activities, such as intellectual-property theft. Both newspapers’ framing aligns broadly with U.S. government narratives and policies towards China, reflecting underlying political and ideological biases.

