	abstract = {The Russian invasion of Ukraine on 24 February 2022 ignited propaganda efforts from the U.S. executive branch of government and the U.S. media, as the country tried to position itself towards the war not just in the eyes of its citizens but of the entire world as part of its geopolitical power position. A comparative quantitative and qualitative analysis of official U.S. communications and U.S. partisan media coverage in the first week of the invasion aims to uncover how the U.S. government set the agenda and framed the events, and to what extent the media copied or diverged from this agenda-setting and framing. The results suggest a narrow focus and distinct framing on the part of the U.S. government, partly taken over by partisan media. The latter also touched on other topics that fit media logic and provided some counter-frames in line with their ideological positions, yet overall confirmed the dominant framing of the war as unjust, unprovoked and premeditated, as Putin’s choice, and the position of the U.S. as the leader of the free world and defender of democracy.},
	language = {en},
	number = {1},
	urldate = {2025-03-30},
	journal = {Journalism and Media},
	author = {Hyzen, Aaron and Van Den Bulck, Hilde},
	month = feb,
	year = {2024},
	pages = {233--254},
	annote = {Brief Summary:
Hyzen and Van den Bulck analyze U.S. propaganda strategies during the initial week of the Russia–Ukraine war. They assess how the U.S. government and partisan media set agendas and framed the conflict. They highlight a dominant narrative framing Russia’s invasion as “unjustified, unprovoked, and premeditated,” clearly attributing blame to Putin personally. The authors identify that this messaging actually reinforced U.S. identity as a defender of global democracy, employing historical Cold War rhetoric contrasting freedom and democracy (U.S.) against authoritarian aggression (Russia). Partisan media adopted core elements of this framing while introducing counter-frames on specific domestic policy issues, like energy sanctions.

Evaluation:
This paper is highly relevant for my topic, as it directly addresses how U.S. government and partisan media narratives frame nationalism through contrasting portrayals of Russia. Its detailed analysis of framing techniques is inspiring for my methodological approach, particularly through its integration of quantitative and qualitative content analysis. Notably, the paper emphasizes media alignment with official narratives, a dimension I will expand by explicitly comparing left- and right-leaning media frames. I will investigate framing consistency over a longer period and across diverse geopolitical contexts, not just immediate responses during the crisis events.
},
	file = {PDF:/Users/apple/Zotero/storage/NF7Z53M7/Hyzen and Van Den Bulck - 2024 - “Putin’s War of Choice” U.S. Propaganda and the Russia–Ukraine Invasion.pdf:application/pdf},
}

